Mammary tissues without lymph nodes from two mice of each genotype were collected, frozen in liquid nitrogen, and stored at -80 °C. Total RNA was extracted using TRIzol reagent, followed by a cleanup step using the RNeasy Plus Mini Kit (QIAGEN). Poly(A) RNA was purified twice from 1 mg total RNA and cDNA was synthesized using SuperScript II (Invitrogen) and TruSeq RNA Sample Preparation Kit (Illumina Inc., San Diego, CA), and sequenced using HiSeq 2000 (Illumina).

description: Fertile_hpv6w_SP1_42 years;	This placental sample is of first  trimester normal pregnancy, underwent elective surgical termination. It is the first of eight, 6 weeks biological replicates sample, each from different individual woman.
extract_protocol_ch1: Placental samples were collected in sterile ice-cold phosphate buffered saline (PBS, pH 7.4). The tissue samples were quickly washed in ice-cold PBS to remove blood and debris, and separated from surrounding membranes, and villous portions were dissected from decidual and embryonic tissue under a dissecting microscope and further washed with sterile, cold PBS. The total RNA was extracted using Trizol (Agilent Technologies Singapore Pvt. Ltd., Shung Avenue, Singapore) and cleaned up with DNase I (Sigma Chemical Co., St. Louis, Missouri, USA) and subjected to re-extraction when it was necessary. The yield and purity of the extracted RNA was checked using standard spectrophotometric method and 1% agarose gel electrophoresis. Furthermore, RIN score of individual sample was determined using Bioanalyzer, RNA Chip kit and Software from Agilent Technologies (Santa Clara, CA, USA).

description: X690_E.CEL;	Pool of 8-15 individuals from an inbred line derived from a natural population in Raleigh, North Carolina (kindly provided by the laboratory of Dr. Trudy F. C. Mackay, NC State University)
treatment_protocol_ch1: Prior to injection, the bacterial culture was grown in LB broth + streptomycin (100µg/ml) from a single colony of a streptomycin resistant strain of Escherichia coli until OD600 reached 1.0 ± 0.1 (Beckman DU-65 Spectrophotometer, Beckman, Fullerton, CA, USA), corresponding to a final concentration of approximately 5.5x10^8 colony forming units/ml.  The bacterial solution was then loaded into pulled-glass capillary needles.  Bacteria-filled capillary needles were connected to an Eppendorf Femtojet microinjector (Eppendorf, Westbury, NY, USA) and flies were injected with the same volume of E. coli in the abdomen (microinjector settings: injection pressure = 0.46, injection time = 0.2s, and compensation pressure = 0.20) or were sham-injected with sterile Ringer's solution. Bacterially infected and sham-injected flies from each of the lines at each time point were frozen at -80°C six hours post-injection
extract_protocol_ch1: Total RNA was extracted using the TRIzol extraction method, followed by an RNeasy cleanup, according to the manufacturer’s instructions (Invitrogen/Qiagen).

treatment_protocol_ch1: Prior to injection, the bacterial culture was grown in LB broth + streptomycin (100µg/ml) from a single colony of a streptomycin resistant strain of Escherichia coli until OD600 reached 1.0 ± 0.1 (Beckman DU-65 Spectrophotometer, Beckman, Fullerton, CA, USA), corresponding to a final concentration of approximately 5.5x10^8 colony forming units/ml.  The bacterial solution was then loaded into pulled-glass capillary needles.  Bacteria-filled capillary needles were connected to an Eppendorf Femtojet microinjector (Eppendorf, Westbury, NY, USA) and flies were injected with the same volume of E. coli in the abdomen (microinjector settings: injection pressure = 0.46, injection time = 0.2s, and compensation pressure = 0.20) or were sham-injected with sterile Ringer's solution. Bacterially infected and sham-injected flies from each of the lines at each time point were frozen at -80°C six hours post-injection
extract_protocol_ch1: Total RNA was extracted using the TRIzol extraction method, followed by an RNeasy cleanup, according to the manufacturer’s instructions (Invitrogen/Qiagen).

Bacteria-filled capillary needles were connected to an Eppendorf Femtojet microinjector (Eppendorf, Westbury, NY, USA) and flies were injected with the same volume of E. coli in the abdomen (microinjector settings: injection pressure = 0.46, injection time = 0.2s, and compensation pressure = 0.20) or were sham-injected with sterile Ringer's solution. Bacterially infected and sham-injected flies from each of the lines at each time point were frozen at -80°C six hours post-injection
extract_protocol_ch1: Total RNA was extracted using the TRIzol extraction method, followed by an RNeasy cleanup, according to the manufacturer’s instructions (Invitrogen/Qiagen).

The TURBO DNase treatment or RNeasy kit in conjunction with the RNase-Free DNase Set was used to further purify the initial RNA isolation according to the manufacturer’s recommendations. The DNA-free RNA isolations with ABS 260/280 ratios above 1.7 and two distinct peaks representing the 18S and 28S ribosomal RNA and minimal background banding, were selected for analysis.

treatment_protocol_ch1: From each patient, matched tissue parts from the peripheral and the central tumor area were snap frozen immediately after operation and stored at -80°C. Tissue specimens were histologically confirmed to represent either the tumor infiltration zone (INF) or cell-rich central tumor areas (CEN) and then subjected to subsequent microdissection.
extract_protocol_ch1: Total RNA was extracted by calcium chloride ultracentrifugation.

At least 400ng of Dnase I-treated total RNA was used for library construction. As per published protocols, cDNA that was synthesized using oligo(dT) beads was digested with NlaIII and then ligated to an Illumina specific adapter containing the MmeI recognition sequence. Following digestion, a second Illumina adapter was added that contained a 2bp degenerate 3' overhang. The adapters were used to amplify by PCR and the products were run on a 12% PAGE gel.
